title: Worked Solution
text:
To determine whether the value $$y= rac{4}{3}$$ is a solution to the equation $$9y+2=6y+3$$, we can substitute $$ rac{4}{3}$$ for $$y$$ in the equation and see if it holds true.
Substituting $$ rac{4}{3}$$ for $$y$$ in the equation gives us:
$$9\left( rac{4}{3}ight)+2=6\left( rac{4}{3}ight)+3$$
Simplifying this expression gives us:
$$12+2=8+3$$
Which simplifies to:
$$14=11$$
Since $$14$$ does not equal $$11$$, $$y= rac{4}{3}$$ is not a solution to the equation $$9y+2=6y+3$$.
